Docker is a platform that enables developers to build, package, and run applications inside containers — lightweight, portable units that include everything needed to run the software (code, runtime, libraries, dependencies).

🔑 Key Concepts
Container → Isolated environment for running applications.

Image → Blueprint for a container (built from a Dockerfile).

Dockerfile → Script with instructions to build an image.

Docker Hub → Public registry for sharing images.

Docker Engine → Core runtime that executes containers.

⚙️ How Docker Works (Real‑Time Flow)
Developer writes a Dockerfile → Defines base image, dependencies, and commands.

Build an image → docker build -t myapp .

Run a container → docker run -p 8080:8080 myapp

Test locally → Application runs in isolated environment.

Push to registry → docker push myapp → Share with team.

Deploy anywhere → Same container runs on dev machine, test server, or cloud (AWS, GCP, Azure).

🚫 Common Errors in Real Projects
Image build errors → Wrong Dockerfile syntax or missing dependencies.

Port conflicts → Container port already in use.

Volume mount issues → Incorrect path mapping between host and container.

Networking errors → Containers can’t communicate due to misconfigured bridge networks.

Resource limits → Containers crash if CPU/memory quotas are exceeded.

✅ Bottom Line: Docker makes applications portable, consistent, and easy to deploy, forming the backbone of modern DevOps and microservices architectures.

🧹 Container Management
docker ps → List running containers

docker ps -a → List all containers (including stopped)

docker run -d -p 8080:80 nginx → Run container in detached mode, map ports

docker stop <container_id> → Stop a running container

docker start <container_id> → Start a stopped container

docker restart <container_id> → Restart container

docker rm <container_id> → Remove container

📦 Image Management
docker images → List images

docker build -t myapp . → Build image from Dockerfile

docker pull ubuntu:20.04 → Download image from Docker Hub

docker push myrepo/myapp → Push image to registry

docker rmi <image_id> → Remove image

📂 Volumes & Data
docker volume ls → List volumes

docker volume create myvolume → Create volume

docker run -v myvolume:/data myapp → Mount volume to container

docker run -v /host/path:/container/path myapp → Bind mount host directory

🌐 Networking
docker network ls → List networks

docker network create mynet → Create custom network

docker run --network=mynet myapp → Attach container to network

docker inspect <container_id> → View container details (IP, config)

🔧 Debugging & Logs
docker logs <container_id> → View container logs

docker exec -it <container_id> bash → Open interactive shell inside container

docker inspect <container_id> → Detailed info about container

docker stats → Show resource usage (CPU, memory)

🚀 Docker Compose
docker-compose up -d → Start services in background

docker-compose down → Stop and remove services

docker-compose ps → List running services

docker-compose logs → View logs for services

✅ Bottom Line: These commands cover running containers, managing images, handling volumes, networking, debugging, and multi‑container setups with Docker Compose — everything you’ll need for real‑world projects and interviews.

📊 Docker Architecture Overview
Docker Client

CLI (docker run, docker build) or GUI tools.

Sends commands to the Docker Daemon.

Docker Daemon (Engine)

Core service that manages images, containers, networks, and volumes.

Runs on the host machine.

Images

Read‑only templates used to create containers.

Built from Dockerfiles.

Containers

Running instances of images.

Lightweight, isolated, portable.

Volumes

Persistent storage for containers.

Decouples data from container lifecycle.

Networks

Enable communication between containers.

Bridge, host, overlay, custom networks.

Registry (e.g., Docker Hub, AWS ECR)

Stores and distributes images.

Developers push/pull images here.

🗣️ Interview Narration Tip

“Docker architecture is built around the Docker Engine, which manages images and containers. Developers interact with Docker through the client, which sends commands to the daemon. Images are stored in registries like Docker Hub, pulled into the engine, and run as containers. Volumes provide persistent storage, and networks allow containers to communicate. This architecture makes applications portable and consistent across environments.”

