📄 Basic Structure of a Dockerfile

# 1. Base image
FROM openjdk:17-jdk-slim

# 2. Set working directory inside container
WORKDIR /app

# 3. Copy application files into container
COPY target/myapp.jar /app/myapp.jar

# 4. Define command to run application
CMD ["java", "-jar", "myapp.jar"]

🔑 Common Dockerfile Instructions
FROM → Defines the base image (e.g., ubuntu, openjdk, node).

WORKDIR → Sets the working directory inside the container.

COPY → Copies files from host to container.

RUN → Executes commands during image build (e.g., install packages).

CMD → Default command to run when container starts.

EXPOSE → Declares the port the app listens on.

ENV → Sets environment variables.

🧠 Best Practices
Use small base images (e.g., alpine) to reduce size.

Keep layers minimal (combine RUN commands).

Use .dockerignore to avoid copying unnecessary files.

Pin versions for reproducibility.

Separate build and runtime stages with multi‑stage builds.

✅ Bottom Line: A Dockerfile is your blueprint for creating consistent, portable containers.

📄 Multi‑Stage Dockerfile (Java/Maven)

# -------- Stage 1: Build --------
FROM maven:3.8.8-openjdk-17 AS build

# Set working directory
WORKDIR /app

# Copy pom.xml and download dependencies first (caching optimization)
COPY pom.xml .
RUN mvn dependency:go-offline -B

# Copy source code and build
COPY src ./src
RUN mvn clean package -DskipTests

# -------- Stage 2: Runtime --------
FROM openjdk:17-jdk-slim

# Set working directory
WORKDIR /app

# Copy only the built artifact from build stage
COPY --from=build /app/target/myapp.jar ./myapp.jar

# Expose application port
EXPOSE 8080

# Run the application
CMD ["java", "-jar", "myapp.jar"]

🔑 Why Multi‑Stage?
Smaller final image → Only contains JDK + JAR, not Maven or source code.

Faster builds → Dependencies cached in Stage 1.

Security → No unnecessary build tools in runtime image.

Portability → Same image runs in dev, test, and production.

🗣️ Interview Narration Tip

“In real projects, I use multi‑stage Dockerfiles. The first stage uses Maven to build the JAR, and the second stage runs it with a slim JDK image. This keeps the final image lightweight and secure, while ensuring reproducible builds in CI/CD pipelines.”

